  "text": "Kafka's Java-based service lifecycle is primarily implemented in the Connect framework and supplemented by Streams and server utilities. The Herder interface (Herder.java) defines the lifecycle contract with start()/stop() methods. AbstractHerder implements startServices() which starts Worker -> StatusBackingStore -> ConfigBackingStore, and stopServices() which stops them in reverse order (StatusBackingStore -> ConfigBackingStore -> Worker). Connect.java orchestrates the top-level lifecycle: start() starts herder then REST, stop() stops REST then herder (reverse order). StandaloneHerder and DistributedHerder provide concrete implementations with coordinated shutdown (halt() in DistributedHerder stops connectors/tasks before calling stopServices()). KafkaStreams implements AutoCloseable with start() launching global then stream threads, and close/shutdownHelper stopping stream threads first then global thread, then state directory, admin client, and metrics. The Scheduler interface and KafkaScheduler provide a startup()/shutdown() lifecycle pattern used by broker internals. ShutdownableThread provides a base class for graceful thread lifecycle with initiateShutdown()/awaitShutdown() coordination via CountDownLatch.",
